: 465;2007: 2025; 2010: NA)","English: probably a shortened form of   Thornton  , or a habitational name from Thorton in Marnhull, Dorset, which has the same origin."]},{"name":"Skehan","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Sceacháin</b> or <b>Ó Sceacháin</b> ‘son (or descendant) of <i>Sceachán</i>’, a personal name probably based on a diminutive of <i>sceach</i> ‘briar, thorn bush’. The Gaelic name has sometimes been ‘translated’ as   Thornton  ."]}]},{"name":"Wimar","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: variant of   Simard   and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."],"variants":[{"name":"Simard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Marcel, Lucien, Andre, Alphonse, Armand, Fernand, Gaston, Jacques, Emile, Germain, Gilles, Gisele.","French: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sigmar</i>, composed of the elements <i>sigi</i> ‘victory’ + <i>mari</i>, <i>meri</i> ‘famous’.","History: Pierre Simard <i>dit</i> Lombrette from Puymoyen in Charente, France, married Suzanne Durand in Angoulême in Charente in 1635, died probably in Beaupré, QC, <i>c.</i> 1685."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":19,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705188,"age":28,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Ga